=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default">
									<p>In the past, light sources were usually specified in watts to d=
escribe their <a href=3D"https://www.emilum.com/blog/wissen/einheiten-von-l=
icht/#lux">brightness</a>. The approach =E2=80=9Cthe more power, the bright=
er=E2=80=9D was basically ok within a technology (e.g. light bulb), but it =
no longer makes sense when <strong>comparing with other light sources</stro=
ng>, as the efficiency<a href=3D"https://www.emilum.com/blog/wissen/einheit=
en-von-licht/#lichtausbeute">(luminous efficacy</a>) differs here. <br>Toda=
y, this practice has changed and the brightness is specified in <a href=3D"=
https://www.emilum.com/blog/wissen/einheiten-von-licht/#lumen">lumens</a>, =
which better describes the actual light output of a light source and is muc=
h more meaningful. In this article, we explain the <strong>differences betw=
een watts and lumens</strong> and how to compare and calculate these units.=
 Finally, we give tips on what you should look out for when selecting light=
 sources.   </p>								</div>
