									<p><strong>No!</strong> The LED industry is constantly researching=
 and developing, which in turn results in ever better LEDs (more informatio=
n on <a href=3D"https://www.emilum.com/blog/wissen/led-tutorial/">light-emi=
tting diodes</a>). Every luminaire manufacturer has the choice of which LED=
s to install in their luminaires. The choice here is huge, in simple terms =
from cheap to efficient. In addition, LEDs with a <a href=3D"https://www.em=
ilum.com/blog/wissen/farbtemperatur/">cooler color temperature</a> (more bl=
ue component) <span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">are more efficien=
t than the more popular warm white LEDs</span>. As described above, the <a =
href=3D"https://www.emilum.com/blog/wissen/einheiten-von-licht/#cri">color =
rendering index</a> also has a strong effect on the luminous efficacy. Fina=
lly, how well the manufacturer has mastered <strong>thermal design</strong>=
 (an important quality criterion! <span style=3D"text-decoration: underline=
;">The cooler the LEDs</span> are operated, the <span style=3D"text-decorat=
ion: underline;">more efficient </span>and <span style=3D"text-decoration: =
underline;">the longer-lasting</span> the <a href=3D"https://www.emilum.com=
/led-leuchten/">LED luminaire</a>) and how efficiently the control electron=
ics have been designed.     </p>								</div>
